{This is a game played between two players with identical blitz rating, but a
big difference on Long time control rating. White is a master level player on
long time control with a rating of 2349, while Black in long time control is
rated 1999.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Nf6 7.
d3 d6 8. Nc3 h6 9. a4 Rb8 10. axb5 axb5 11. Nd5 O-O 12. Be3 Nxd5 13. Bxc5 {
on this move White took nearly 10 seconds, showing the importance of thinking
before taking back.} Nf4 14. Be3 Ng6 15. Bd5 (15. c3 $5) 15... Nce7 16. Ba7 Bg4
17. Bxb8 Nxd5 18. exd5 Qxb8 {Black is trying to create imbalances in a
position which looked equal.} 19. h3 Bd7 20. Qd2 Qc8 {By this point White has
3 minutes, and Black 4. The point obviously is: Can Black create a checkmate
attack sacrificing on H3?} 21. Qb4 {On this move White spent nearly 40 seconds!
} (21. d4 {the engine would play this move, but this is a critical point in
the game.}) 21... Nf4 22. Nh2 Qd8 {Now it was Black's turn to think, and gave
this move around 15 seconds.} (22... Bxh3 $4 23. gxh3 Qxh3 24. Qe4 f5 25. Qf3 {
And White stops Black's checkmating attempt, and has a clear advantage.}) (
22... Qb7 23. Ng4 Qxd5 24. Ne3 Qb7 {the position is still equal.}) 23. Kh1 Nxd5
24. Qb3 Nf4 25. Qb4 Qg5 {White seems passive, while Black is trying to build
up an attack on the kingside.} 26. Qe4 $6 {Black is better, the idea now is
White doesn't have enough time to stop Be6-d5, especially in a blitz game!} (
26. Rg1 Ne2 27. Rgd1 Nf4 $11) 26... f5 {By this point White has 1 minute and
37 seconds, and Black has 2 minutes and 36 seconds.} (26... Be6 $1 {how to
stop Bd5?}) 27. Qf3 Be6 28. Qg3 Qf6 29. Ra7 Bd5 30. f3 Nh5 31. Qf2 Qg6 32. Rfa1
e4 33. Rxc7 {White is trying to get counter-play on the 7th rank.} exd3 34.
cxd3 Re8 (34... f4 $5 {this move would have created 2 outposts, and blocked an
escape square for the Kh1.}) 35. Nf1 Nf4 36. Raa7 Ne6 {Maybe the move White
missed! It controls G7, and gives Black some peace of mind. For Komodo White
is winning, and has a +4 advantage!} 37. Rd7 {White has only 42 seconds left.
Black 1 minute and 31 seconds.} f4 38. Rxd6 Qf5 39. Rdd7 $6 {White has only 23
seconds left.} Rc8 40. Qd2 Qe5 41. d4 Qf5 {18 seconds left for White.} 42. Qe2
Rc1 43. Qxb5 $4 $11 {10 seconds left for White.} Rxf1+ $4 $18 (43... Qb1 $1 {
Black didn't find the right move, but I think at this point he was trying to
flag the opponent.} 44. Rxg7+ Nxg7 45. Qxd5+ Kh7 46. Rxg7+ Kxg7 47. Qe5+ {
And now White gives endless checks to draw the game.}) 44. Qxf1 Kh7 45. Qb5 $6
Qb1+ 46. Kh2 Qg6 {7 seconds left for White.} 47. Qxd5 $4 $11 (47. Rxd5 $1 $18
Qg3+ 48. Kg1 Qe1+ 49. Qf1 {White wins materially, but still the problem is
time, with less than 5 seconds left, White is doomed to lose.}) 47... Qg3+ 48.
Kg1 Qe1+ 49. Kh2 Qg3+ 50. Kg1 Qe1+ 51. Kh2 Qg3+ 52. Kg1 Qg6 {Here the computer
calculates a checkmate in 8 moves.} 53. Qe4 $6 Qxe4 {3 seconds left for White.
Both side are just moving instantaneously.} 54. fxe4 Kg6 55. d5 Nd4 56. Rxg7+
Kf6 57. Rae7 Ne2+ {and here White played Rgf7, and Black claimed the win,
showing he would eat the king! This is part of the Blitz rules of the United
States Chess Federation, as written in the US Chess Federation rules of chess,
6th edition, page 311, rule 7d Who after an illegal move is completed by the
opponent, takes the king, (if the king is in check) or claims the win and
stops the clock, before the player determines a move, and provided the player
has sufficient mating material as defined in rule 7c.} 0-1

